<p style="padding:5px 0;font-family:'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;font-weight: 400;font-size:16px;line-height:25.6px;margin:0;">My first question is: why do we need <a href="https://amp.dw.com/en/humanoid-robots-outrun-humans-at-beijing-half-marathon/video-76857300" style="text-decoration: underline; color: #b61313 !important;">robots that can outrun humans</a>?&nbsp;</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;font-family:'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;font-weight: 400;font-size:16px;line-height:25.6px;margin:0;">Let&#8217;s rewind a bit. Last year in China, humans raced robots and won by almost three hours. In the same race on Sunday, the winning robot <a href="https://techcentral.co.za/humanoid-robots-are-now-faster-than-the-worlds-best-runners/280366/" style="text-decoration: underline; color: #b61313 !important;">beat humans</a> by over 10 minutes. If you look closely, this is an extended metaphor for how fast technology is closing gaps that once felt impossible.</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;font-family:'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;font-weight: 400;font-size:16px;line-height:25.6px;margin:0;">Now imagine what this could unlock in our part of the world&mdash;reaching flooded areas faster, moving supplies across rough terrain, responding to emergencies, and okay, maybe finally getting your package delivered on time.</p>
